theory of zombieism.

00:47:27.460 --> 00:47:28.820
AUDIENCE: Like [? latents. ?]

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:30.090
TIM VERSTYNEN: Yeah.

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:33.840
The real phenomenon that I think
fascinates me the most in this

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.930
is toxoplasmosis.

00:47:35.930 --> 00:47:38.120
So toxoplasmosis is a
single-cell organism.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:40.020
It's what lives in cat poop.

00:47:40.020 --> 00:47:41.640
And it's why pregnant
women shouldn't

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:44.230
be around cat poop
is because it induces

00:47:44.230 --> 00:47:47.080
flu-like symptoms if
you get the infection.

00:47:47.080 --> 00:47:50.770
And it can be dangerous to
fetuses and young children.

00:47:50.770 --> 00:47:53.070
But normally, if you're
an adult and you get it,

00:47:53.070 --> 00:47:54.920
you just get a flu and
it seems to go away.

00:47:54.920 --> 00:47:58.490
But really what happens is it's
a single-cell organism that

00:47:58.490 --> 00:48:01.945
reproduces sexually in the
gut of a feline, right,

00:48:01.945 --> 00:48:04.070
so that's where it gets
its most genetic diversity.

00:48:04.070 --> 00:48:07.990
When it's outside the feline,
it can only reproduce asexually,

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:09.670
so it clones itself.

00:48:09.670 --> 00:48:12.235
So what this organism does
is, even after the infection,

00:48:12.235 --> 00:48:14.520
it stays latent in your system.

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:20.070
And in the mammals that it
infects-- rodents, humans--

00:48:20.070 --> 00:48:24.470
it actually starts modifying
the neuropharmacology

00:48:24.470 --> 00:48:26.100
of the individual's brain.

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:29.080
And what you see is, you see
characteristic behavioral

00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:33.290
differences in people who have
had toxoplasmosis and survive

00:48:33.290 --> 00:48:34.900
versus those who don't.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:36.660
And the most
classic case of this

00:48:36.660 --> 00:48:38.180
was an experimental
study where they

00:48:38.180 --> 00:48:41.000
took a rat-- and rats
normally hate cats,

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.216
they're instinctively
afraid of cats-- gave it

00:48:43.216 --> 00:48:46.880
a toxoplasmosis intervention,
and across time,

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:50.090
if you had a glass wall
between the rat and the cat,

00:48:50.090 --> 00:48:52.180
normally the rat's over here.

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:54.290
But as the infection
rate occurs,

00:48:54.290 --> 00:48:55.930
the rat actually
starts to not only

00:48:55.930 --> 00:48:59.080
not be afraid, but want
to be near the cat.

00:48:59.080 --> 00:49:02.140
So there's increased
risk-taking behavior

00:49:02.140 --> 00:49:04.110
that happens as a
result of the infection.

00:49:04.110 --> 00:49:06.340
And actually, that same
kind of behavior-- not

00:49:06.340 --> 00:49:08.780
towards cats, obviously, but
more risk-taking behavior

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:11.520
is seen in human individuals
who've had the infection.

00:49:11.520 --> 00:49:13.620
So somehow, the
single-cell organism

00:49:13.620 --> 00:49:15.690
is hijacking the
complex circuits

00:49:15.690 --> 00:49:19.060
that induce our ability to
be afraid of certain things

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:20.640
and increase risk taking.

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:23.290
So that, coupled with the
kind of popularization

00:49:23.290 --> 00:49:24.820
of the infection
theory of zombies,

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:26.880
I think, is the more
interesting link there.

00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:29.860
And if you were going to ask
me about biologically possible,

00:49:29.860 --> 00:49:33.222
with the caveat that it's still
